00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:50.015
so this for example is the
JavaScript editor.

00:17:50.015 --> 00:17:55.080
It comes with a set of
JavaScript file icons and is

00:17:55.080 --> 00:17:57.910
mapped to the JavaScript
[INAUDIBLE].

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:06.270
And if you are creating a
new document, then this

00:18:06.270 --> 00:18:06.853
URL would be called.

00:18:06.853 --> 00:18:10.240
And we distinguish the different
file types by their

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:11.990
sub-domain.

00:18:11.990 --> 00:18:16.510
And so once our application gets
called the first Create

00:18:16.510 --> 00:18:20.270
time with this Create action,
then we can create the proper

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:24.920
file type and redirect the user
more or less to our main

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:26.500
Editey application.

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:29.050
So they are all working
on the same

00:18:29.050 --> 00:18:30.790
application, on App Engine.

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:34.960
So that's important to allow
people to share files and

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:36.560
stuff like that.

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:43.690
But to get a different file
icons, we had to create this

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:48.580
application and the Google API
console for each file type.

00:18:48.580 --> 00:18:50.180
STEVE BAZYL: This is something
that we could probably

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:53.500
certainly make easier for
applications like yourself,

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:56.575
like yours, where you create
different types of content

00:18:56.575 --> 00:18:59.990
with the same application and
wanting to have those

00:18:59.990 --> 00:19:02.480
represented as distinct
actions.

00:19:02.480 --> 00:19:05.050
So definitely something that
we'll add to that to the list

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:06.970
of feature requests.

00:19:06.970 --> 00:19:08.590
DANIEL FLOREY: It really depends
where you want to have

00:19:08.590 --> 00:19:09.450
the complexity.

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:14.670
Because if you allow multiple
file items and icons in the

00:19:14.670 --> 00:19:18.460
API console, then the console
itself may get quite

00:19:18.460 --> 00:19:19.490
complicated.

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:24.510
But really, from a user
perspective it would be really

00:19:24.510 --> 00:19:28.500
nice if you were to have a
Create menu on Google Drive.

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:33.190
Maybe with a sub menu for the
different file types that an

00:19:33.190 --> 00:19:35.910
application can handle
and create.

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:38.460
But maybe it's just a very
special case, I don't know.

00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:42.110
But probably other users
may come up with the

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:44.200
same request as well.

00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:50.420
STEVE BAZYL: The downside to
having multiple applications

00:19:50.420 --> 00:19:54.420
is you end up having to
authorize multiple application

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:55.550
to read the content.

00:19:55.550 --> 00:19:57.890
So if you're constantly
switching between content, or

00:19:57.890 --> 00:20:00.350
at least that first couple times
of loading all those

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:04.230
apps and authorizing could
be a little bit onerous.

00:20:04.230 --> 00:20:05.990
But they're really cool apps.

00:20:05.990 --> 00:20:09.290
And I've actually installed
these on my own account and

00:20:09.290 --> 00:20:10.740
have started using them.

00:20:10.740 --> 00:20:15.290
They're really nicely done, and
I love that they're very

00:20:15.290 --> 00:20:19.030
familiar to myself, certainly,
as somebody who uses Docs on a

00:20:19.030 --> 00:20:21.180
daily basis.

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:25.530
It feels like it's just another
version of Google Docs

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:26.410
that handles all the--

00:20:26.410 --> 00:20:28.710
DANIEL FLOREY: I think if you're
a small company, I

00:20:28.710 --> 00:20:31.970
think it's really my
recommendation to stay with

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:36.380
something that a bigger
company has developed.

00:20:36.380 --> 00:20:40.240
So for example, Twitter
Bootstrap, I think that's

00:20:40.240 --> 00:20:44.580
quite great instead of starting
to create your own

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:47.400
style sheets and stuff
like that.

00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:50.640
If you're a small company,
why try to

00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:51.840
reinvent everything yourself?

00:20:51.840 --> 00:20:56.540
So I think it's just fair
to just more or

00:20:56.540 --> 00:20:57.460
less copy their layout.

00:20:57.460 --> 00:21:00.860
Especially if you're focusing
on the same user base.

00:21:00.860 --> 00:21:05.450
And I think it's also good
for the Google Drive--

00:21:05.450 --> 00:21:07.540
be consistent with all
the applications.

00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:09.060
Look at least a little
bit familiar.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:13.920
STEVE BAZYL: Certainly we
encourage people to have their

00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:17.960
own brand, but having certain
conventions, and usability

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:20.310
standards, and everything really
helps in making users

00:21:20.310 --> 00:21:23.930
feel comfortable with those
applications and reduce that

00:21:23.930 --> 00:21:24.490
learning curve.

00:21:24.490 --> 00:21:28.110
So great job on those
applications.

00:21:28.110 --> 00:21:31.255
Do you have-- other than, it was
a great trick with showing

00:21:31.255 --> 00:21:33.130
the multiple applications.

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:36.180
Is there anything else that
comes to mind that developers

00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:40.210
who might be thinking about
building apps for Drive--

00:21:40.210 --> 00:21:45.410
tips that you might share, or
any advice for how to be

00:21:45.410 --> 00:21:47.180
successful?

00:21:47.180 --> 00:21:50.150
DANIEL FLOREY: I think maybe
when starting a new

00:21:50.150 --> 00:21:55.840
application I think it's really
a good idea to find out

00:21:55.840 --> 00:22:01.790
what is the right granularity
if you want to share stuff.

00:22:01.790 --> 00:22:09.130
Because it makes sense to take
most of functionality that is

00:22:09.130 --> 00:22:13.200
available, like sharing and
revision history and maybe

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:16.220
real time API and all the stuff
that you get more or

00:22:16.220 --> 00:22:16.735
less for free.

00:22:16.735 --> 00:22:19.790
You just have to provide
a nice user interface.

00:22:19.790 --> 00:22:24.890
But the product part is
already done for you.

00:22:24.890 --> 00:22:28.830
And so I think you have to make
sure that you find the

00:22:28.830 --> 00:22:32.470
right size of pieces
that you want to

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:34.300
share with other users.

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:37.880
For example, if it comes to
contact sharing I think it

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:41.290
would not make much sense to
have this file item on Google

00:22:41.290 --> 00:22:42.580
Drive for each contact.

00:22:42.580 --> 00:22:47.490
Maybe it would make sense to
have one icon or one item for

00:22:47.490 --> 00:22:49.580
a contact group, or whatever.

00:22:49.580 --> 00:22:54.810
So I think if you find the
proper size of items that you

00:22:54.810 --> 00:22:58.190
want to share and you want to
work on, then you can really

00:22:58.190 --> 00:23:00.000
take a lot of advantage
from the

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:03.100
features that are available.

